's groups are working independently in Thailand to promote women's rights. The aim of this study is to document the strategies adopted by a selection of these groups, and the programmes that they are implementing in Thailand, in order to understand how cultural specificity (of mobility and education) guides their participation, and how gender relations are formed and transformed. While attempting to synthesize the disparate data collected on Thai women and their organizations, the authors have tried to evolve an analytical framework to study the meaning and significance of women's lives and efforts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Jun 2018) 0aFeminismzThailandxCase studies. 0aWomenzThailandxSocieties and clubsxCase studies.1 aPandey, Shashi Ranjan, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Publishing ebook Package Archive 1970-1999z978311060669040uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/9789814376273423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814376273.jpg  a978-3-11-060669-0  ISEAS Publishing ebook Package Archive 1970-1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG